comment:
Generally speaking, I don't believe in cancel culture - If it turns out that my favourite singer was a domestic abuser, would  that mean their music is now shit? No, their art still remains superb, even if the individual is a piece of crap. That said, Johnny Depp has already been thrown out of his film(s) despite the mountain of evidence that Amber was the abuser.

For that reason alone, this was the first (and probably the last time) where I cast my vote to have her removed from Aquaman. I don't like becoming part of the cancel culture, even for this one exception, and if Johnny Depp wasn't being cancelled himself, I would watch Amber's films as well, despite her being a domestic abuser on her previous relationships as well (because that has nothing to do with her art, in my opinion), but enough is enough.

I'm a real person and I wasn't paid, I happily signed the petition for the reason I explained above, and I'm trying to be up to date with the matter just in case new evidence comes out proving me wrong. So far I'm definitely with Depp.

comment:
I signed the petition as well.  I'm a real person, I subscribe to AMC's A-List program and go to the movies (at least before theaters closed earlier this year) several times a month.  I also sat through hours of audio tape listening to Heard describe how she physically and emotionally abused Johnny Depp and engaged in gaslighting during these conversations/arguments/etc.  It was, at times, heartbreaking listening to her essentially attempt to squash and tear down the spirit of a man who is clearly a kind and thoughtful individual.  A man who had *never* before been accused of being of being violent with anyone let alone his partners, the very same partners who have been coming out in support of Depp.  

Heard on the other hand has been arrested by police who witnessed her being physically abusive to her (then) partner, at which point they attempted to change the narrative and accused the officer of discrimination until it came out that the officer was actually a member of the LGBTQ community.  Furthermore, she claimed that things were so bad at times that she was in fear for her life, yet more often than not, the taped conversations show Heard aggressively arguing, yelling and/or insulting her alleged abuser.  This is, of course arguably, contrary to common behavior for the abused party in a relationship.  Things don‚Äôt always have to make sense, but it‚Äôs contradictory behavior for someone who is being abused (who is afraid for their life during a fight with their partner) to provoke their alleged abuser by making a habit  of throwing things at them and it makes zero sense to berate someone for bailing from an escalating argument.  Which is it?  Did she want him to stay or was she afraid of him?

So, the purported reason Warner Bros. finally asked Depp to resign after the Sun trial verdict was due to their parent company‚Äôs policy of zero tolerance for...‚Äùshenanigans‚Äù.  That‚Äôs their prerogative of course, even if they‚Äôll lose money because people disagree with them and intend to boycott the film. But, if Warner Bros. is going to enforce a zero tolerance policy, regardless of the fact that the trial outcome has drawn intense criticism (the weight given to The Sun‚Äôs witnesses who have axes to grind with Depp but never uttered a bad word prior to the divorce, the reversal of burden of proof, an apparent disregard for the plaintiff‚Äôs evidence and several points of conflict of interest) even though Depp is likely to continue to pursue an appeal (with existing legal precedence), then they need to equally enforce that policy.  There is more than sufficient evidence in the form of audio where Heard admits to being violent, among other problematic behavior (such as lying to Australian gov‚Äôt after breaking the law and soliciting others to lie on her behalf to avoid punishment), and zero tolerance is zero tolerance.  So, she too should be subject to the same policy if for no other reason (namely the 1.7m people and climbing who don‚Äôt want to see her return to Aquaman) than there is clear evidence of her violent behavior (her admissions on audio) where the evidence against Depp is almost entirely circumstantial.  

It‚Äôs time for an end to double standards because equality doesn‚Äôt only matter when a particular gender or race is fighting for it.  Time is up indeed.

comment:
If Johnny Depp was removed from the "Fantastic Beasts" franchise because he is in the midst of legal proceedings to clear his name from allegations of domestic abuse that he was never arrested for, or charged with...then Amber Heard *NEVER SHOULD HAVE BEEN HIRED FOR AQUAMAN* in the first place.  In 2009, *long before she met Johnny Depp,*  she was arrested for the domestic assault of her partner, Tasya van Ree, which was witnessed by the arresting officers as well as an international airport full of people.  She attempted to have her record expunged, but the press uncovered her secret.  Amber Heard then suborned *HER VICTIM* , Ms. van Ree, to release a *false statement* in an attempt to clear her name.  The *lies were exposed* when the arresting officer, Officer Beverly Leonard came forward with the *TRUTH!* Amber Heard is a pathetic attempt of a feminist.  "Treat me just as you would treat a man, unless that means holding me *accountable* for my *OWN* actions!"  

Warner Brothers may not feel the need to hold men and women equally responsible--but they will soon learn that the fans are happy to boycott a film that stars a known domestic abuser.  In the end, Mr. Depp has all the evidence needed to clear his name, and hold Ms. Heard accountable for her crimes, in the Virginia Trial (where the Judge *doesn't* have multiple connections to Amber Heard and her lawyers).  As for the British Trial, it is still under appeal (in my country, Judge Nicol would lose his position for not recusing himself because of his son's employment connection to Dan Wooton).  It is only a matter of time before Ms. Heard is arrested for domestic assault again.  Narcissistic abusers repeat their patterns.  Warner Brothers will discover that Ms. Heard is a substantial liability.
